  {"id":"Barid_Baran_V_I","name":"Barid Baran V I","initials":"BB","dept":"EIE","title":"Freedom, Democracy and the Cost of Silence","tags":["civic","society"],"summary":"My speech discussed how freedom is not permanently guaranteed in any democracy and can gradually decline when citizens become indifferent.","conclusion":"Freedom is not sustained by constitutional documents alone but by active citizens."},
 {"id":"Sunanda_V_K","name":"Sunanda V K","initials":"SU","dept":"EIE","title":"The Magic of Our Brains","tags":["philosophy","society"],"summary":"When we compare the human brain to a computer, we often borrow the wrong language. That is where the confusion begins. We say the brain stores information and retrieves memories, just like a machine. But the brain doesn't work like a hard drive. Instead, when we recall a memory, we don't simply pull out a file, we re-experience the moment. The sights, the sounds, and the emotions come alive again. To show this, I involved my classmates in a small activity, helping them feel how vivid and personal memory truly is. Another fascinating aspect of the brain is its ability to grow and adapt. Unlike computers, the brain improves by forming new neural connections and even creating new neurons. This incredible flexibility allows us to adjust to new environments, learn continuously, and evolve with every experience. In short, the brain isn't just a machine. It is a living, ever-changing system that reshapes itself with every thought and memory.","conclusion":""},

 {"id":"Sanjay_Eshwaran_P","name":"Sanjay Eshwaran P","initials":"SE","dept":"EIE","title":"Presentation by Sanjay Eshwaran P","tags":["society"],"summary":"
Talent is not just an advantage, it is a head start hard work can't fully match. A talented person learns faster, adapts quicker, and performs effortlessly. Hard work helps, but without talent, growth has limits. A natural left-handed person writes smoothly, while a trained one still struggles. That instinct cannot be fully created through practice. Talent gives efficiency, hard work gives repetition. In competition, efficiency wins. You can train someone day and night to become a world-class singer. But without natural voice control, can they compete with a talented person? Hard work improves, but talent defines the peak.","conclusion":"Talent is greater than hard work."},

